📊 Sentiment Analysis with RoBERTa
📌 Project Overview

This project applies Natural Language Processing (NLP) techniques to analyze customer reviews and classify them into sentiment categories (Negative, Neutral, Positive).
It combines basic EDA & preprocessing with a pre-trained RoBERTa model (Hugging Face) for state-of-the-art sentiment classification.

🚀 Features

Load and explore a dataset of customer reviews.

Perform Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) on review ratings.

Text Preprocessing using NLTK (tokenization, stopwords, etc.).

Fine-tune and apply RoBERTa (cardiffnlp/twitter-roberta-base-sentiment) for sentiment analysis.

Convert model logits into probabilities using Softmax.

Generate sentiment scores dictionary (roberta_neg, roberta_neu, roberta_pos).

🛠️ Tech Stack

Python 3

Pandas, NumPy → data handling

Matplotlib, Seaborn → visualization

NLTK → text preprocessing

Transformers (Hugging Face) → pre-trained RoBERTa model

PyTorch → deep learning backend

📂 Dataset

Dataset used: Amazon Fine Food Reviews
 (or your provided Reviews.csv)

Contains product reviews with Text and Score columns.

⚙️ Installation

Clone the repo and install dependencies:

git clone https://github.com/your-username/sentiment-analysis-roberta.git
cd sentiment-analysis-roberta
pip install -r requirements.txt


If you’re using Jupyter Notebook:

pip install notebook
jupyter notebook

▶️ Usage

Run the notebook step by step:

Load data

df = pd.read_csv("Reviews.csv")


Preprocess and tokenize text

from transformers import AutoTokenizer, AutoModelForSequenceClassification
tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained("cardiffnlp/twitter-roberta-base-sentiment")


Run sentiment analysis

encoded_text = tokenizer("I love this product!", return_tensors="pt")
output = model(**encoded_text)


Convert to sentiment scores

scores = softmax(output[0][0].detach().numpy())
print({"Negative": scores[0], "Neutral": scores[1], "Positive": scores[2]})

📊 Example Output
{'roberta_neg': 0.02, 'roberta_neu': 0.15, 'roberta_pos': 0.83}

